<!--
  Pi-hole VM: Wazuh agent <localfile> blocks.

  Append this inside any <ossec_config> block in the Pi-hole VM's
  /var/ossec/etc/ossec.conf, then restart the agent:
      sudo systemctl restart wazuh-agent

  Multiple <ossec_config> blocks at the top level are valid Wazuh
  syntax; the agent merges them at load time. Easiest pattern is to
  drop a new <ossec_config> below the stock ones rather than splice
  into existing blocks.

  Single source: /var/log/vault-dns/events.log

  Structured JSON log emitted by the FTL-DB sidecar at
  sidecar/pihole/pihole-ftl-tail.py. One line per Vault VM DNS query, with
  fields qtype / query / status / status_code / blocked / forward.

  Lives in its own subdirectory so logrotate can target the dir
  cleanly. Rotation handled by /etc/logrotate.d/vault-dns (host-side
  config; canonical text in Vaultwarden/README.md § Log Rotation →
  LAN Pi-hole VM): daily, keep 14 compressed.

  log_format=json tells the agent to ship raw JSON lines; Wazuh's
  built-in JSON decoder on the manager auto-extracts every key into
  data.* fields, so manager-rules.xml just filters by field=value
  without needing a custom decoder.

  Earlier iterations also tailed /var/log/pihole/pihole.log (text-log
  approach, retired) and /var/log/pihole/FTL.log (daemon health,
  optional). Both are gone now: the sidecar reads the FTL SQLite
  database directly, so the host bind mount of /var/log/pihole has
  been removed from PiHole/docker-compose.yml and those host paths no
  longer exist. If you're upgrading from either earlier state, REMOVE
  any leftover <localfile> for /var/log/pihole/* from your deployed
  ossec.conf when you add the entry below.
-->

<ossec_config>

  <localfile>
    <log_format>json</log_format>
    <location>/var/log/vault-dns/events.log</location>
  </localfile>

</ossec_config>
